WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
I'm Walter Lewin.

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:08.000
I will be your lecturer
this term.

3
00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:10.000
In physics, we explore the
very small to the very large.

4
00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:16.000
The very small is a small
fraction of a proton

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:19.000
and the very large is
the universe itself.

6
00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:22.000
They span 45 orders
of magnitude--

7
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:25.000
a 1 with 45 zeroes.

8
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.000
To express measurements
quantitatively

9
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:34.000
we have to introduce units.

10
00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:37.000
And we introduce for the unit
of length, the meter;

11
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:43.000
for the unit of time,
the second;

12
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:47.000
and for the unit of mass,
the kilogram.

13
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Now, you can read in your book
how these are defined

14
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:55.000
and how the definition
evolved historically.

15
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Now, there are
many derived units

16
00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:01.000
which we use in our daily life
for convenience

17
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:05.000
and some are tailored
toward specific fields.

18
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:08.000
We have centimeters,
we have millimeters

19
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:11.000
kilometers.

20
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
We have inches, feet, miles.

21
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Astronomers even use
the astronomical unit

22
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.000
which is the mean distance
between the Earth and the sun

23
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.000
and they use light-years

24
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:23.000
which is the distance that
light travels in one year.

25
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.000
We have milliseconds,
we have microseconds

26
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:29.000
we have days, weeks, hours,
centuries, months--

27
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:33.000
all derived units.

28
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:35.000
For the mass, we have
milligrams, we have pounds

29
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:39.000
we have metric tons.

30
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:42.000
So lots of derived units exist.

31
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:47.000
Not all of them are
very easy to work with.

32
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:50.000
I find it extremely difficult
to work with inches and feet.

33
00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:53.000
It's an extremely
uncivilized system.

34
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:56.000
I don't mean to insult you,
but think about it--

35
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:58.000
12 inches in a foot,
three feet in a yard.

36
00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Could drive you nuts.

37
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.000
I work almost
exclusively decimal,

38
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
and I hope you will do the same
during this course

39
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.000
but we may make some exceptions.

40
00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.000
I will now first show you
a movie,

41
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:14.000
which is called
The Powers of Ten.

42
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:17.000
It covers 40 orders
of magnitude.

43
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:19.000
It was originally conceived
by a Dutchman named Kees Boeke

44
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:23.000
in the early '50s.

45
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:25.000
This is the second-generation
movie, and you will hear

46
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:29.000
the voice of Professor Morrison,
who is a professor at MIT.

47
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:36.000
The Power of Ten--
40 Orders of Magnitude.

48
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:43.000
Here we go.

49
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:54.000
I already introduced,
as you see there

50
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:56.000
length, time and mass

51
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:59.000
and we call these

52
00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:01.000
the three fundamental quantities
in physics.

53
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:05.000
I will give this the symbol
capital L for length

54
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:09.000
capital T for time,
and capital M for mass.

55
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:12.000
All other quantities in physics
can be derived

56
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:16.000
from these fundamental
quantities.

57
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:19.000
I'll give you an example.

58
00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:22.000
I put a bracket around here.

59
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:24.000
I say speed, and that means
the dimensions of speed.

60
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:28.000
The dimensions of speed is
the dimension of length

61
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000
divided by the dimension
of time.

62
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.000
So I can write for that:
[L] divided by [T].

63
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Whether it's meters per second
or inches per year

64
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:41.000
that's not what matters.

65
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:42.000
It has the dimension
length per time.

66
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Volume would have
the dimension

67
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:50.000
of length to the power three.

68
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Density would have
the dimension

69
00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:00.000
of mass per unit volume

70
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:05.000
so that means
length to the power three.

71
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:09.000
All-important in our course
is acceleration.

72
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:13.000
We will deal a lot
with acceleration.

73
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Acceleration, as you will see,
is length per time squared.

74
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:20.000
The unit is meters
per second squared.

75
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:23.000
So you get length
divided by time squared.

76
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:31.000
So all other quantities
can be derived

77
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:33.000
from these three fundamental.

78
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.000
So now that we have agreed
on the units--

79
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:39.000
we have the meter,
the second and the kilogram--

80
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:42.000
we can start making
measurements.

81
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.000
